Hmm, let's see. Suppose you want to display a progress message, as in "Progress is integer%" where "integer" is a varying integer. A simple way to do that would be to create a loop that adds one to your integer and prints the new string, but if you use \n, it'll print each new string in a new line, which defeats the purpose. You want a string in which only the integer changes, and you can do that using \r.

To make this easier to understand, here's a simple C++ program that you can run to see this in action.

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int main() {
for (int i = 0; i <= 100; ++i)
cout << "The progress is: " << i << "%\n";
return 0;
}

This code will print out the same sentence a 100 times, on a 100 different lines, while incrementing the integer progress value. You don't want your program to do that; you want it to keep changing the integer value without printing new lines, and for that, you can use \r. Try it yourself to see what happens. Good luck.
